May 4, 2026
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO IMPOSE A LIMITED MORATORIUM ON INITIATING CERTAIN SURFACE
3 WATER TRANSFERS FROM THE CAPE FEAR RIVER BASIN, TO DIRECT THE
4 NORTH CAROLINA COLLABORATORY TO STUDY THE CAPE FEAR RIVER
5 BASIN, AND TO MAKE CERTAIN REVISIONS TO THE ENVIRONMENTAL
6 MANAGEMENT COMMISSION'S AUTHORITY TO REQUIRE REDUCTIONS TO
7 EXISTING SURFACE WATER TRANSFERS FROM ANY RIVER BASIN IN THE
8 STATE.
9 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
10
11 PART I. CAPE FEAR WATER RESOURCES
12
13 LEGISLATIVE PURPOSE AND FINDINGS
14 SECTION 1.(a) Title. ‒ This Part shall be known as the Cape Fear Water Resources
15 Modernization and Regionalization Act of 2026.
16 SECTION 1.(b) Legislative Findings. – The General Assembly finds that the State's
17 laws regulating surface water transfers, originally enacted more than 30 years ago, should be
18 comprehensively reviewed and evaluated for updates in light of the State's and, in particular, the
19 Cape Fear River Basin's tremendous economic and population growth and the impacts of drought
20 and natural disasters on riverine and water reservoir systems over that period. The General
21 Assembly finds that the approval of new or modified transfers that substantially diminish the
22 overall hydrologic flow, current and future water storage capacity, and water quality of the Cape
23 Fear River Basin should be temporarily paused while this review and evaluation is ongoing.
24 SECTION 1.(c) Legislative Purpose. – The purpose of this Part is to ensure the
25 sustainable use and protection of the Cape Fear River Basin's water resources by temporarily
26 pausing new surface water transfers from the upper reaches of the Cape Fear River Basin while
27 a comprehensive review is conducted.
28
29 MORATORIUM ON NEW OR INCREASED INTERBASIN TRANSFERS FROM THE
30 UPPER REACHES OF THE CAPE FEAR RIVER BASIN
31 SECTION 2.(a) Definitions. – The definitions set forth in G.S. 143-215.22G apply
32 to this section.
33 SECTION 2.(b) Moratorium on New or Increased Interbasin Transfers. – There is
34 hereby established a moratorium on the initiation of new surface water transfers or increases in
*H1136-v-1*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 existing surface water transfers from any source in the Cape Fear River Basin located upstream
2 of Cape Fear Lock and Dam #2 in Bladen County. The Environmental Management Commission
3 shall not issue a certificate authorizing a new surface water transfer or an increase in an existing
4 surface water transfer from any source in the Cape Fear River Basin located upstream of Cape
5 Fear Lock and Dam #2.
6 SECTION 2.(c) Exceptions. – The moratorium established by subsection (b) of this
7 section shall not prohibit the following surface water transfers from the Cape Fear River Basin:
8 (1) Any existing transfers authorized by the Environmental Management
9 Commission or else lawfully initiated prior to the effective date of this act. No
10 person who maintains an existing transfer under this subdivision shall increase
11 the amount of surface water transferred to another river basin.
12 (2) Any emergency transfer of surface water authorized by the Secretary of
13 Environmental Quality under G.S. 143-215.22L(q) or G.S. 143-355.3.
14 SECTION 2.(d) Moratorium Duration. – This section is effective when it becomes
15 law and expires June 1, 2030.
16
17 CAPE FEAR RIVER BASIN STUDY
18 SECTION 3.(a) Study. – The North Carolina Collaboratory at the University of
19 North Carolina at Chapel Hill (Collaboratory) shall study the Cape Fear River Basin to determine
20 its reliable yield of water supply and make recommendations for any legislative changes
21 necessary to ensure the sustainability of existing and future in-basin water uses. The
22 Collaboratory shall include all of the following in its study:
23 (1) A catalog of the existing water uses and users of the Cape Fear River Basin.
24 (2) An assessment of the reliable yield of water supply of the Cape Fear River
25 Basin, including an assessment for each of its subbasins and major tributaries.
26 This assessment shall include a scientific evaluation of the quantity of water
27 that can be dependably withdrawn or transferred under current and projected
28 future hydrologic conditions without causing unacceptable environmental or
29 economic impacts to in-basin uses.
30 (3) An analysis of the adequacy of the environmental impact study requirements
31 for interbasin transfers from sources in the Cape Fear River Basin located
32 upstream of Cape Fear Lock and Dam #2.
33 (4) An assessment of the economic equity of interbasin transfers for affected
34 communities within the Cape Fear River Basin.
35 (5) An examination of any anticipated water quality and ecological impacts from
36 approved and proposed interbasin transfers from the Cape Fear River Basin.
37 SECTION 3.(b) Consultation. – In collecting and analyzing data relevant to
38 determining reliable yield of water supply from the Cape Fear River Basin, the Collaboratory
39 shall consult with the United States Army Corps of Engineers, the Department of Environmental
40 Quality, the Environmental Management Commission, the State Water Infrastructure Authority,
41 the North Carolina League of Municipalities, and other relevant public and private entities
42 responsible for impoundments and water supply infrastructure in the Cape Fear River Basin.
43 SECTION 3.(c) Report. – The Collaboratory shall report its findings, together with
44 any proposed legislation, to the General Assembly no later than July 1, 2029.
45 SECTION 3.(d) Appropriation. – There is appropriated from the General Fund to
46 the Board of Governors of The University of North Carolina the sum of one million five hundred
47 thousand dollars ($1,500,000) in nonrecurring funds for the 2026-2027 fiscal year to be allocated
48 to the North Carolina Collaboratory to fund the study of the Cape Fear River Basin described in
49 subsection (a) of this section. These funds shall not revert to the General Fund at the end of the
50 2026-2027 fiscal year but shall remain available until the end of the 2028-2029 fiscal year.
51 SECTION 3.(e) Effective Date. – This section becomes effective July 1, 2026.
