2 PART II. EMC AUTHORITY TO REQUIRE REDUCTIONS TO EXISTING
3 INTERBASIN TRANSFERS
4 SECTION 4. G.S. 143-215.13(d) reads as rewritten:
5 "(d) The Commission may conduct a public hearing pursuant to the provisions of this
6 subsection in any area of the State, whether or not a capacity use area has been declared, when it
7 has reason to believe that the withdrawal of water from or the discharge of water pollutants to
8 the waters in such area is having an unreasonably adverse effect upon such waters. If the
9 Commission determines that withdrawals of water from or discharge of water pollutants to the
10 waters within such area has resulted or probably will result in a generalized condition of water
11 depletion or water pollution within the area to the extent that the availability or fitness for use of
12 such water has been impaired for existing or proposed uses and that injury to the public health,
13 safety or welfare will result if increased or additional withdrawals or discharges occur, the
14 Commission may issue a rule:
15 (1) Prohibiting any person withdrawing waters in excess of 100,000 gallons per
16 day from increasing the amount of the withdrawal above such limit as may be
17 established in the rule.
18 (2) Prohibiting any person from constructing, installing or operating any new well
19 or withdrawal facilities having a capacity in excess of a rate established in the
20 rule; but such prohibition shall not extend to any new well or facility having
21 a capacity of less than 10,000 gallons per day.
22 (3) Prohibiting any person discharging water pollutants to the waters from
23 increasing the rate of discharge in excess of the rate established in the rule.
24 (4) Prohibiting any person from constructing, installing or operating any facility
25 that will or may result in the discharge of water pollutants to the waters in
26 excess of the rate established in the rule.
27 (5) Prohibiting any agency or political subdivision of the State from issuing any
28 permit or similar document for the construction, installation, or operation of
29 any new or existing facilities for withdrawing water from or discharging water
30 pollutants to the waters in such area in excess of the rates established in the
31 rule.
32 (6) Requiring any person who maintains an existing surface water transfer from
33 one river basin to another to reduce the amount of transfer to such rates
34 established in the rule.
35 The determination of the Commission shall be based upon the record of the public hearing
36 and other information considered by the Commission in the rulemaking proceeding. The rule
37 shall describe the geographical area of the State affected thereby with particularity and shall
38 provide that the prohibitions set forth therein shall continue pending a determination by the
39 Commission that the generalized condition of water depletion or water pollution within the area
40 has ceased.
41 …."
42 SECTION 5.(a) G.S. 143-215.22L(n) reads as rewritten:
43 "(n) Final Determination: Certificate Conditions and Limitations. – The Commission may
44 grant the certificate in whole or in part, or deny the certificate. The Commission may impose any
45 conditions or limitations on a certificate that the Commission finds necessary to achieve the
46 purposes of this Part including a limit on the period for which the certificate is valid. The
47 conditions and limitations shall include any mitigation measures proposed by the applicant to
48 minimize any detrimental effects within the source and receiving river basins. In addition, the
49 certificate shall require all of the following conditions and limitations:
50 (1) A water conservation plan that specifies the water conservation measures that
51 will be implemented by the applicant in the receiving river basin to ensure the
House Bill 1136-First Edition Page 3

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 efficient use of the transferred water. Except in circumstances of technical or
2 economic infeasibility or adverse environmental impact, the water
3 conservation plan shall provide for the mandatory implementation of water
4 conservation measures by the applicant that equal or exceed the most stringent
5 water conservation plan implemented by a public water system that withdraws
6 water from the source river basin.
7 (2) A drought management plan that specifies how the transfer shall be managed
8 to protect the source river basin during drought conditions or other
9 emergencies that occur within the source river basin. Except in circumstances
10 of technical or economic infeasibility or adverse environmental impact, this
11 drought management plan shall include mandatory reductions in the permitted
12 amount of the transfer based on the severity and duration of a drought
13 occurring within the source river basin and shall provide for the mandatory
14 implementation of a drought management plan by the applicant that equals or
15 exceeds the most stringent water conservation plan implemented by a public
16 water system that withdraws water from the source river basin.
17 (3) The maximum amount of water that may be transferred, calculated as a daily
18 average of a calendar month, and methods or devices required to be installed
19 and operated that measure the amount of water that is transferred.
20 (4) A provision that the Commission may amend a certificate to reduce the
21 maximum amount of water authorized to be transferred whenever it appears
22 that an alternative source of water is available to the certificate holder from
23 within the receiving river basin, including, but not limited to, the purchase of
24 water from another water supplier within the receiving basin or to the transfer
25 of water from another sub-basin within the receiving major river basin.
26 (5) A provision that the Commission shall amend the certificate to reduce the
27 maximum amount of water authorized to be transferred if the Commission
28 finds that the applicant's current projected water needs are significantly less
29 than the applicant's projected water needs at the time the certificate was
30 granted.
31 (5a) A provision that the Commission shall amend the certificate to reduce the
32 maximum amount of water authorized to be transferred if the Commission
33 finds that a reduction is necessary to avoid detrimental effects on the source
34 river basin, including present and future effects on public, industrial,
35 economic, recreational, and agricultural water supply needs, wastewater
36 assimilation, water quality, fish and wildlife habitat, electric power
37 generation, navigation, and recreation.
38 (6) A requirement that the certificate holder report the quantity of water
39 transferred during each calendar quarter. The report required by this
40 subdivision shall be submitted to the Commission no later than 30 days after
41 the end of the quarter.
42 (7) Except as provided in this subdivision, a provision that the applicant will not
43 resell the water that would be transferred pursuant to the certificate to another
44 public water system. This limitation shall not apply in the case of a proposed
45 resale or transfer among public water systems within the receiving river basin
46 as part of an interlocal agreement or other regional water supply arrangement,
47 provided that each participant in the interlocal agreement or regional water
48 supply arrangement is a co-applicant for the certificate and will be subject to
49 all the terms, conditions, and limitations made applicable to any lead or
50 primary applicant."
